":"about 1235","1261":"1261","Abt 1268":"about 1268","1260":"1260","1316":"1316","Bef 1273":"before 1273","1236":"1236","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","18 de June de 1261":"18 June 1261","1329":"1329","Holywell, Flintshire, Wales":"Holywell, Flintshire, Wales","Inglaterra":"England","Castle Rising, Norfolk, England":"Castle Rising, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Harden, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cheshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Mohaut was born about 1235, in Castle Rising, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Roger de Montalt and Cecily d'Aubigny. He married Joan de Mowbray in 1261, in Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died before 1273, in Holywell, Flintshire, Wales."},"et":{"Abt 1235–Bef 1273":"umbes 1235–enne 1273","1235–1273":"1235–1273","1236–1273":"1236–1273","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1243–1284":"1243–1284","1263–1329":"1263–1329","1265–1296":"1265–1296","1268–1316":"1268–1316","1210–1260":"1210–1260","–1261":"–1261","18 June 1260":"18. juuni 1260","1263":"1263","1296":"1296","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","Abt 1235":"umbes 1235","1261":"1261","Abt 1268":"umbes 1268","1260":"1260","1316":"1316","Bef 1273":"enne 1273","1236":"1236","1268":"1268","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1265":"1265","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","18 de June de 1261":"18. juuni 1261","1329":"1329","Holywell, Flintshire, Wales":"Holywell, Flintshire, Wales","Inglaterra":"England","Castle Rising, Norfolk, England":"Castle Rising, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harden, Flintshire, Wales":"Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cheshire, Inglaterra, Reino Unido":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1235–Bef 1273":"noin 1235–ennen vuotta 1273","1235–1273":"1235–1273","1236–1273":"1236–1273","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1243–1284":"1243–1284","1263–1329":"1263–1329","1265–1296":"1265–1296","1268–1316":"1268–1316","1210–1260":"1210–1260","–1261":"–1261","18 June 1260":"18. kesäkuuta 1260","1263":"1263","1296":"1296","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","Abt 1235":"noin 1235","1261":"1261","Abt 1268":"noin 1268","1260":"1260","1316":"1316","Bef 1273":"ennen vuot